# Tracking and Documentation Standards

## Excel Tracking Sheet

### Location and Purpose
- Excel tracking sheet is located in the Doc folder
- Used to document all changes across releases
- Serves as a central repository for change history
- Facilitates cross-module impact analysis
- Supports automation requirements

### Required Fields
- Script name and path
- Script version (YYYYMMDD format)
- Scriptset version
- Module dependencies
- Change description
- Affected modules
- Cross-module impacts
- Automation requirements
- Developer and reviewer information
- Date of change

### Update Process
- Update Excel sheet with every change
- Include all affected scripts
- Document dependencies
- Note cross-module impacts
- Specify automation requirements
- Validate completeness before submission

### Automation Integration
- Excel sheet should be updated as part of CI/CD pipeline
- Automated validation of required fields
- Integration with version control system
- Automated dependency checking
- Cross-reference with script versions

## Version Tracking

### Script Version Format
- Follow YYYYMMDD format (e.g., 20250106)
- Update in script header
- Update in Begin_Release file
- Consistent across all related scripts

### Version Update Requirements
- Always update scriptversion in header
- Add comment line describing changes
- Update scriptsetversion in Begin_Release file
- Update Begin_Release file even if only subfiles change
- Ensure version consistency across modules
- For individual script execution, increment DBVERSION_NR for each script (e.g., 9700001, 9700002, 9700003)
- Set V_DBVERSION_REQ to the previous script's V_DBVERSION_NR before each script execution

### Dependency Version Requirements
- Document required dependent DBVERSION (e.g., 9500001)
- Set dependent module prefix (e.g., NLALL2_3)
- Validate dependency versions before execution
- Document version dependencies in Excel sheet

